Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation Sources Service
DUKE ENERGY KENTUCKY, INC.
RATE SCHEDULE NO. 14
Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation Sources Service
Duke Energy Kentucky, Inc. ("Duke Energy Kentucky") provides Reactive Supply and Voltage from Generation Sources Service ("Reactive Supply Service") from various generating facilities to the PJM Interconnection, LLC ("PJM") system. This Rate Schedule sets forth Duke Energy Kentucky's revenue requirements for the provision of Reactive Supply Service to PJM, as contemplated by Schedule 2 of the PJM open access transmission tariff. This Rate Schedule shall be effective upon the date authorized by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.

MARKET-BASED RATE TARIFF
OF
DUKE ENERGY KENTUCKY, INC.
Tariff Volume No. 1
MARKET-BASED RATE TARIFF
OF
DUKE ENERGY KENTUCKY, INC.
Tariff Volume No. 1
1. Availability: Duke Energy Kentucky, Inc. ("DEK" or "Seller") makes electric energy and capacity and ancillary services available under this tariff at market-based rates for wholesale sales to purchasers with whom DEK has contracted. All transactions under this tariff shall be voluntary.
2. Applicability: This tariff is applicable to all market-based wholesale sales of electric energy and capacity and ancillary services by DEK not otherwise subject to a particular rate schedule of DEK.
3. Rates: All sales shall be made at rates established by agreement between the purchaser and DEK.
4. Other Terms and Conditions: All other terms and conditions of sale shall be established by agreement between the purchaser and DEK. 5. Ancillary Services: a. RTO/ISO Specific PJM: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ("PJM") and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection. New York: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc. New England: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc.
California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation ("CAISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO. MISO: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute supplemental reserve and 30 minute short term reserve) for sale to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. ("MISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to MISO. SPP: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to Southwest Power Pool, Inc. ("SPP") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to SPP. b. Third Party Provider Third-party ancillary services: Seller offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve-Supplemental Reserves, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to a Regional Transmission Organization ("RTO") or an independent system operator ("ISO"), i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider's OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization. 6. Compliance with Commission Regulations: Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning Seller's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes Seller to engage in affiliate sales under this tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the seller's market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning Seller's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this tariff.
7. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority:
a. Limitations: DEK does not have authority under this tariff to make sales within the Duke Energy Carolinas balancing authority area, the Duke Energy Progress balancing authority areas, or in the Peninsular Florida balancing authority areas except for the following ones: Florida Power & Light, Florida Municipal Power Pool, JEA, Seminole Electric Cooperative, Tampa Electric Company, City of Tallahassee, Gainesville Regional Utilities, and City of Homestead (the "Mitigated Markets"). See Duke Power, a Div. of Duke Energy Corp., 111 FERC ? 61,506, at P 61 (2005) (limitation on market-based rate sales within the Duke Energy Carolinas balancing authority area); Florida Power Corp., 113 FERC ? 61,131, at P 17 (2005) (limitations on market-based rate sales within the Progress Energy Carolinas balancing authority areas and Peninsular Florida); see also Duke Energy Corp., 136 FERC ? 61,245 (2011); Duke Energy Corp., 139 FERC ? 61,194 (2012)., see also Duke Energy Florida, LLC ., 179 FERC ? 61,141 (2022) (modification of Duke Energy Florida's market-based rate authority in Peninsular Florida). Any sales by DEK within the Mitigated Markets will be made in accordance with the rate schedules approved by the Commission prior to DEK commencing such sales. Peninsular Florida is defined for purposes of this tariff as all of that portion of the State of Florida lying to the east of Florida Power Corporation's ("FPC") points of interconnection with Gulf Power Company, and to the south of the points of interconnection of those transmission lines jointly owned by Florida Power & Light Company and Jacksonville Electric Authority with Georgia Power Company and south of the points of interconnection of the City of Tallahassee and FPC with Georgia Power Company. See DeSoto County Generating Co., 106 FERC ? 61,100 (2004).
b. Sales to Market-Regulated Power Sales Affiliates in MISO: Pursuant to Cincinnati Gas & Electric Company, 113 FERC ? 61,197 (2005) and Cinergy Corp., 128 FERC ? 61,102 (2009), DEK may make sales in the MISO to an affiliate that is a market-regulated power sales affiliate pursuant to the terms of this tariff, provided however that in no case may such sale be made at a rate that is lower than, on an after-the fact comparison basis, the locational marginal price applicable at the time of sale, reported at the MISO Cinergy Hub or the Indiana Hub if and when the MISO replaces the Cinergy Hub with the Indiana Hub.
c. Sales to Market-Regulated Power Sales Affiliates in PJM: Pursuant to Cincinnati Gas & Electric Company, 113 FERC ? 61,197 (2005), Cinergy Corp., 128 FERC ? 61,102 (2009), and Duke Energy Kentucky, Inc., 136 FERC ? 61,001 (2011), DEK may make sales in PJM of capacity and energy to an affiliate that is a market-regulated power sales affiliate pursuant to the terms of this tariff, provided however that in no case may such sale of capacity be made at a rate that is lower than the PJM Final Duke Zonal Capacity Price or may such sale of energy be made at a rate which is lower than, on an after-the fact comparison basis, the locational marginal price applicable at the time of sale, reported at the PJM Duke Energy Load Zone. 8. Modifications: Seller may unilaterally apply, under Federal Power Act Section 205 and the regulations promulgated thereunder, to the Commission or other regulatory agency having jurisdiction for a modification of this tariff. 9. Seller Category: Seller is a Category 2 seller in the Northeast Region, and a Category 1 seller in other regions (Central, Northwest, Southeast, Southwest, and Southwest Power Pool regions), as defined in 18 C.F.R. ? 35.36(a).
